res/ — off-device build scripts and source data
================================================

Python scripts here produce the binary assets bundled under mobile/src/main/assets/.

build_lightpollution_grid.py
    Writes the PTSKLP01 light-pollution Bortle grid (bortle.bin).

    The copy of bortle.bin currently committed to
      mobile/src/main/assets/lightpollution/bortle.bin
    is a SYNTHETIC PLACEHOLDER generated by build_synthetic_placeholder() in
    that script.  It is seeded with a few city hotspots and ocean nodata cells
    for development and testing only — it does NOT represent real sky-brightness
    observations.

    The real asset will be produced by the offline packer track (later phase),
    which reads NASA VIIRS/NPP VNP46A4 annual composites and applies the
    Duriscoe et al. (2018) skyglow model.  That pipeline will call write_grid()
    from the same script and replace this placeholder without changing the format.

skyglow/  (Python package: numpy + scipy only)
    Clean-room skyglow propagation kernel + FFT convolution — the scientific
    core that turns an upward-radiance field into an artificial sky-brightness
    field (Garstang 1986/1989 + Duriscoe et al. 2018; see skyglow/kernel.py for
    the implemented functional form and full citations).

      kernel.py    radial single-scattering propagation kernel; the `aerosol`
                   atmospheric-clarity parameter is the primary tunable knob.
      convolve.py  build a discretised radial kernel and FFT-convolve a radiance
                   raster into an artificial V-band sky-luminance field.
      tests/       pytest shape/mechanics tests (synthetic arrays only).

    Run:  pip install numpy scipy pytest --break-system-packages
          pytest res/skyglow/
    (CI is Gradle-only and does not run these Python tests.)

    A1 is shape-validated only.  Absolute calibration (dark-sky park -> Bortle
    1-2, major city -> Bortle 8-9), real NASA VIIRS VNP46A4 input, and the
    brightness -> mag/arcsec^2 -> Bortle mapping are deferred to later phases
    (A2 / A3).

Other scripts (build_bsc_ptskcat4.py, build_const_ptskcons.py, …) produce the
star catalogue and constellation assets; see their file headers for details.
